[The French compilation of BTV-8 incidence in Europe is very helpful;
particularly since the reporting of some affected countries to the
OIE on the current epizootic is deficient, even erratic. While the UK
submits a weekly follow-up report (10 of them so far), other
countries are less meticulous. OIE's WAHID animal health interface
includes one single 2007 report from the Netherlands, dated 3 Aug
2007. - Mod. AS]

******
[2] Germany, losses in sheep; resistance in fallow deer.
Date: Sat 8 Dec 2007
From: Sabine Zentis
<CVLonghorns@aol.com>


The following is a description of the losses in a valuable flock of
250 sheep kept at Schaaeferhof, Marienheide. The family produces
cheese and yoghurt on the farm where 200 Lacaune dairy sheep are
milked twice a day. The 1st case of bluetongue was seen in August
2007. Up to now, 70 sheep have shown clinical disease, 12 died. 5 out
of 6 rams tested positive of which only 2 showed clinical signs. Milk
yield in the dairy sheep during August [2007] was 50 percent down on
last years' August [2006] and overall milk production for 2007 was 10
percent down compared to 2006. Additional costs (vet charges,
pharmaceuticals) were ca. 1000 Euro [about 1472 USD].

The lambing season will be prolonged and the farmer is already
fearing the worst in terms of problems with stillborn or weak lambs.

Fertility testing of 30 breeding rams on the surrounding farms showed
that 9 rams were infertile, 11 showed a very low fertility and only
10 were 100 percent fertile. Scanning of ewes showed that 15 percent
were barren.

[As to BTV-8 in fallow deer] we have now got first results of the
screening of farmed fallow deer at slaughter. 13 animals were
sampled, of which 7 [were] positive for antibodies but rtPCR negative.
This means that the animals had been infected last year [2006] or
that deer can eliminate the virus rather quickly. The owners claim
they have never seen any disease related problems.

--
Sabine Zentis
Castleview Pedigree English Longhorns
Gut Laach
52385 Nideggen
<http://www.cvlonghorns.de/>

