[3] Germany, alpaca
Date: Sat 8 Dec 2007
Source: The Veterinary Record, 1 Dec 2007 - letters [edited]


Lethal bluetongue virus infection in an alpaca
----------------------------------------------
We would like to report a case of lethal bluetongue virus infection
in an alpaca in Germany. The affected animal was a 5-year-old female
alpaca, born and raised in a flock in a low mountain range area in
central Germany. This area was affected by the bluetongue virus
outbreak in Germany in 2007. Within a radius of 5 km [3.1 miles],
clinically evident bluetongue virus infection in sheep and cattle was
reported, with high mortality in affected sheep.

The alpaca herd was housed in an open stable with unrestricted access
to pasture during daytime, but was kept inside the stable at night
(including dusk and dawn); however, the stable was not completely
protected against flying insects.

Just 3 months before its death the alpaca gave birth to a healthy
offspring, which was weaned at the time of death of the mother. But 4
weeks before the animal died, it showed signs of colic with
recumbency and tympanic abdomen. The animal was degassed via
nasogastric intubation and recovered quickly, but the cause of the
clinical signs remained undetected.

Immediately before the fatal bluetongue virus infection, mother and
offspring were in excellent body condition, and neither showed any
signs of an
underlying disease.

Acute clinical signs started with 'hiccup-like' breathing and a
stertorous sound discernible via auscultation. One hour later the
animal was inappetent, recumbent and lethargic. Then, 7 hours later
the animal was observed coughing and mildly disorientated. A total of
14 hours after the first observation of signs the animal died.

On postmortem examination, the animal showed severe, acute, diffuse,
interstitial and alveolar oedema of the lungs. In the oral cavity,
single small erosions and ulcerations on the tongue, palate and
buccal mucosa could be observed.

As well as postmortem changes and acute congestion of the liver,
spleen and kidneys, histopathology revealed severe congestion,
interstitial and alveolar oedema of the lung, and mild hypertrophy of
type II pneumocytes.

Focal haemorrhages in the tunica media at the base of the pulmonary
artery, a common finding in bluetongue virus infections in sheep,
were not observed.

PCR revealed sequences of bluetongue virus in tissue samples (blood,
lymph nodes and spleen), whereas no sequences of ovine herpesvirus
type 2 were detectable.

The rest of the herd, including the offspring, remain healthy and show no
signs of bluetongue virus infection.

--
Communicated by:
M. Henrich, M. Reinacher,
Institut fur Veterinar-Pathologie,
Justus-Liebig-Universitat Giessen,
Frankfurter Strasse 96, 35392 Giessen, Germany
H. P. Hamann, Landesbetrieb Hessisches
Landeslabor, Manurer Strasse 54, 35396 Giessen, Germany

[The authors rightly indicate the absence of the changes in the base
of the pulmonary artery, which are very typical in sheep bluetongue.
Another change which seems to be lacking (or not observed?) is found
in sheep in the coronary bands of the hooves, which are often
hyperemic, with petechial or ecchymotic hemorrhages.

Though the demonstration, by PCR, of BTV sequences in tissues of the
affected alpaca are suggestive of BTV being the possible causative
agent of the described per-acute clinical picture and PM findings,
such conclusion deserves caution. Experience in BT-endemic countries
has shown that during the peak of the disease season, a significant
percentage of (non-ovine) ruminants may undergo subclinical
inflection, thus the virus may be demonstrated in animals affected by
various other pathogens.

The above report will, hopefully, be followed by additional
observations which may confirm its significance. - Mod.AS]

