[4] Scotland, preparedness
Date: Wed 12 Dec 2007
Source: the Scotsman [abridged, edited]
<http://business.scotsman.com/index.cfm?id=1935342007>


Moredun chief sounds bluetongue warning
---------------------------------------
Moredun Research Institute in Edinburgh is a world-leader at a time
when animal health problems are increasingly becoming a global issue.

Professor Julie Fitzpatrick, the director of Moredun, said in her
annual report published yesterday [11 Dec 2007]:

"There can be no doubt about the threat of infectious diseases to
Scotland and the UK, and their impact on the livestock industry,
parliamentarians, policymakers and the general public.

"The list of diseases considered as exotic to the UK which reached
our shores in recent months include foot-and-mouth, Newcastle
Disease, avian influenza and bluetongue. We have to be ... prepared
for any eventuality."

However, for practical livestock farmers the big fear is that there
could be a serious outbreak of bluetongue in Scotland next year
following the arrival of this disease in East Anglia in September
[2007]. Losses in sheep and cattle have been minimal, but all the
evidence from Europe suggests that the 2008 scenario might be
radically more severe.

Prof. Fitzpatrick said: "Vaccines are under development and are
urgently required. However, the impact of living with such a policy
against bluetongue has not yet been fully thought through. Moredun is
establishing a working group to prepare our input into the
understanding of this disease, which we consider should be seen as a
new endemic disease in the UK."

Bluetongue is viewed by the farming community as the next potential
disease disaster. Compensation has been paid for the losses incurred
through FMD and bird flu, but no such provision exists for bluetongue.

[Byline: Dan Buglass]

--
Communicated by:
FMD News, FMD Surveillance and Modeling Laboratory,
University of California at Davis
<fmdweb@ucdavis.edu>

