[5] EC BTV conference on vaccination
Date: Mon 10 Dec 2007
Source: EU Health and Consumer Protection Directorate General web-site
[edited]
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/controlmeasures/bluetongue_conference_en.htm>


Bluetongue conference on vaccination, Brussels - 16 January 2008
----------------------------------------------------------------
The European Commission is convening a "Conference on vaccination
strategy against bluetongue" that will take place in Brussels in the
Charlemagne building on 16 Jan 2008.

The bluetongue situation in the Community has considerably changed in
the last years. Vaccination is one of the veterinary measures that
can be implemented in an infected territory. Several Member States
have experience on the use of vaccination as a means to limit the
effects of bluetongue. This experience and the opinion of the
Scientific Panel on Animal Health and Welfare of EFSA on vectors and
vaccines were taken into account when drafting Commission Regulation
(EC) No 1266/2007, available at
<http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/site/en/oj/2007/l_283/l_28320071027en00370052.pdf>.

On the basis of the experience gained, and considering the new EU
legislation as regards bluetongue, it is appropriate to discuss the
use of vaccination against bluetongue as a means of controlling the
disease. For this reason the Commission is organising the above
mentioned Conference.

An invitation letter to the bluetongue conference is available at
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/controlmeasures/invitation_bt_conference.pdf>;
for the tentative agenda, see
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/controlmeasures/bt_conf_agenda.pdf>.

--
Communicated by:
EC Health and Consumer Protection mailing list
<sanco-news@ec.europa.eu>

[BTV-8 seems to be continuing its activity in December 2007,
particularly in France where it spreads south-westwards; a map showing
the location of the restriction zones as updated on 7 Dec 2007 can be
seen at
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/controlmeasures/BlueTongue_RestrictedZones.jpg>.

The EC has now realised the potential of this virus to seriously
affect the European farming industry; consequently increasing the
2008 budget dedicated to the fight against animal diseases: the total
EU contribution to these programmes is 70 075 000 Euro (103 178 142
USD), compared to 52 970 000 Euro (77 990 528 USD) in 2007. The
change is mainly due to an increased allocation to counter Bluetongue
disease in many Member states.

See also "Stop the Cull" editorial of Nature Biotechnology of 7 Dec 2007,
<http://www.nature.com/nbt/journal/v25/n12/pdf/nbt1207-1329.pdf>. - Mod.AS]
